passages.text: Health Care | Healthcare Technology & Distribution
Health Catalyst, Inc HCAT | \(\) 3.50\$ In Line | Target Price/Base Case: \(\) 30.00\$ Commentary
Market Capitalization (M) Enterprise Value (M) Shares Outstanding (M) 52- Week Range Average Daily Volume (M) Dividend Yield Free cash flow yield Fiscal Year End
1 Year Price History

This week we had the pleasure of meeting with HCAT's management team at the Health Catalyst Analytics Summit in Salt Lake City. Our key takeaway from the event was that there is a lot going on under the surface as the company continues to roll out Ignite, evolve its portfolio of offerings to better meet clients' needs in the current environment, and right- size the cost structure. While our revenue estimates remain unchanged vs. 2Q earnings (- 1.6% org in '25, 1.7% in '26, and 3.0% in '27), we are raising our EBITDA estimates as HCAT's current cost cutting program materializes, which should result in \(\sim\) 60 MM of EBITDA in 2026. Given this improved margin profile, we are raising our price target to \$4 (6x '26 EBITDA), but retain our In- Line rating on shares given the still- challenging demand environment.

The 3Q pipeline has seen some improvements so far vs. the base case laid out on the 2Q earnings call, but it is still early and overall demand has been impacted by some customers pausing/delaying projects either due to macro concerns and/or a current focus on Ignite implementations 4Q implied EBITDA guide of \(\sim\) 15 MM is the right way to think about the jump off point for 2026, but the company should see some additional benefits flow through in 1H'26 Ignite transitions on track to be largely complete in 1H'26 and are typically 3- 5 year contracts with \(\sim\) 3- 5% price escalators Lots more details on Ignite platform benefits, etc in our full notes below.

- Multi-year journey    
- 2025: \(\sim 160\) platform clients, \(>1100\) app clients    
- 2024: 130 platform clients, \(>1K\) app clients    
- 2023: 109, \(>630\) - Lower headcount this year with less services revs- Platform business is shrinking slightly, but ignite and apps are growing significantly- Al acceleration of apps layer
Ignite, CTO - Dave Ross
- Ignite - bring disparate data sources together into one analytics system- Core technologies need more healthcare-specific solutions

- DevOps    
- Cloud data    
- Infrastructure    
- Cloud computing    
- Data security    
- Access management

- Land and secure data source    
- Unified patient/provider view    
- Standardized medical terminology    
- Data quality/validation    
- Healthcare compliance    
- Interoperability    
- Healthcare-specific content    
- Self-service tools

- Databricks and Microsoft partnerships    
- Reduced risk    
- Best of both worlds    
- Accelerate time to value    
- Moving beyond analytics
Lifepoint Health Case Study

- Got HCAT to reduce unwanted care variation- Installation involved a lot of internal change management- Had a single point of contact with HCAT to improve communication- 10 types of EHRs (Allscripts, Cerner, Epic, Medhost, Meditech, Paragon)- Some EHR vendors allow direct connections and others involve a \(3^{\text{rd}}\) party work around- Lacked performance metrics to drive and maintain change

E.g. sepsis dashboard Can monitor process and outcomes Metrics Also, congestive heart failure, optimizing blood transfusions, reducing repetitive lab tests, optimizing surgical recovery, improving the accuracy and specificity of clinical documentation integrity

- Partnered with HGAT in June 2022, April 2025 program live at 18 facilities and 6 active use cases, program kicked off in 2023- 700 lives saved from this work, 1.2K fewer transfusions, 24K additional patient days at home, met/exceeded financial goals

- Migrations largely complete by mid-2026- Benefits of modern infrastructure    
- Faster data refreshes    
- Elastic compute reduced billion-row reloads by 71%    
- 80% drop in load failures    
- Accelerated data loading    
- 73% faster sources loaded, improvements driven by scaling through scripting and automation    
- Streamlined data integration    
- Shift from flat files to API connections    
- Elastic scalability    
- More concurrent data sources supported without infrastructure upgrades
- Tooling and automation driving speed

- Code conversion tool (99% coverage)    
- Smart verification to reduce false positives    
- Proven migration playbooks    
- Dedicated technical oversight    
- Scalable delivery model
- Have to upscale clients – so have a technical training program to have client data engineers and analysts ready to work in the new environment
Ignite: Foundation for Enabling Impactful AI in Healthcare

- A lot of AI is not bringing the expected value    
- 77% cite immature AI as a barrier    
- Scribes save
- Realizing cost efficiencies

- PowerCosting- Through a more structured process can find additional cost variations- Need to do it at greater scale to better help customers- Takes 9-12 months, but AI can help improve this timeline
- Can charge a little more at agentic AI apps level
- More than give up in services
- Also working on speeding up development cycle, particularly in middle layer to no longer be annual (now 90 days)

- Lifepoint 
- HCAT focused on not just data quality, but also change management
- Internal IT team that works in lockstep
- Still using a ton of internal HCAT resources for data mapping, etc
- HCAT is one of 2 scaled partners (have another smaller one)
- Competition by use case
- HCAT's clinical expertise in the context of data analytics gives them an advantage for clinical applications vs. others for operations

- Delays in pipeline in 2Q informed how mgmt. thought about projects for the rest of the year- Moved a number of things out of the base case into the upside case- 3Q started a bit stronger than expected and HAS is helpful, but not assuming everything bounces back to normal
- Headcount reduction

- Ambulatory TEMS pilots going away (ended 6/30)- Recent restructuring- Going forward, looking to control costs- \(\) 15\(MM 4Q exiting run rate implies\) \ \(60\) MM for 2026 plus doesn't include all of the run rate benefits- \(\) 10.5\(MM in 3Q guide includes\) \ \(4\) MM of restructuring benefits- 4Q implied guide of \(\) 15\(MM is\) \ \(9\) MM- At least a million per Q in addition- Another 10% or so that phases in in 1H'26- At \(\) 75\(MM revenue level
- Board is doing fiduciary responsibility
- Share repo- Debt repayment- And maybe more transformative options- Question of right timing vis-à-vis ignite

- Internal and external candidates being considered- Someone with deep healthcare and technology experience- Leadership experience- Bonus if have previously been a public company CEO- Mindful of company culture
- Look forward to new ideas
- Also moving from Medicity to Ignite (KPI Ninja), that has impacted revenue
- Disrupting self with new technology- Tracking to this year though have been a tad slower because of scope creep

- It's early to talk about buying changes given macro challenges- During transition, customers interested in pocketing savings- Can talk more about adding applications after migration is over- Has delayed certain expansion opportunities- See more expansion levers with Ignite vs. DOS
Very easy to add apps E.g. intelligence layer
- As they add new sources, there is additional sources, or pulling in more data there are upsides to pricing
- Typically 3-5 year contracts
- 3-5% price escalators- DOS was 1 year contracts with 90-day outs with all you can eat and large escalators which sometimes led to frustrating conversations and discounts
- Seeing the most traction in operational and cost management applications and Vitalware
- Given macro pressures
- Those are apps that can be deployed relatively quickly and ROI in months vs years E.g. activity-based costing
VALUATION METHODOLOGYOur valuation methodology is based on a mix of discounted cash flow analysis and relative valuation (multiples).

RISKS1. The company operates in a new, fast-changing, highly competitive industry and the inability to effectively compete will hinder results of operations2. Failure to successfully execute on growth initiatives, business strategies, or operating plans3. Lack of innovation and services that are useful to customers and users4. Changes and developments in regulation that hinders demand for IT products5. Modified or lost relationships with clients and third party providers6. Pace of adoption lagging despite continued investments could impact growth

Evercore ISI's recommendations are based on a stock's total forecasted return over the next 12 months. Total forecasted return is equal to the expected percentage price return plus gross dividend yield. We divide our stocks under coverage into three primary ratings categories, with the following return guidelines:

Outperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be greater than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. In Line- the total forecasted return is expected to be in line with the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. Underperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be less than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. Coverage Suspended- the rating and target price have been removed pursuant to Evercore ISI policy when Evercore is acting in an advisory capacity in a merger or strategic transaction involving this company and in certain other circumstances. Rating Suspended- Evercore ISI has suspended the rating and target price for this stock because there is not sufficient fundamental basis for determining, or there are legal, regulatory or policy constraints around publishing, a rating or target price. The previous rating and target price, if any, are no longer in effect for this company and should not be relied upon.
Prior to October 10, 2015, the "Coverage Suspended" and "Rating Suspended" categories were included in the category "Suspended."

FINRA requires that members who use a ratings system with terms other than "Buy," "Hold/Neutral" and "Sell" to equate their own ratings to these categories. For this purpose, and in the Evercore ISI ratings distribution below, our Outperform, In Line, and Underperform ratings can be equated to Buy, Hold and Sell, respectively.
